					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Vellum codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">162 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>261</height>
										<width>199</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>170</height>
										<width>140</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>162 folios (+ 2 foliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 2 unfoliated paper fleleaves at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>16 quires of 10 leaves each.</p>
									<p>Quires marked with catchwords on the last page and signed with Hebrew letters on the first and last pages.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Folios 157-161 have the lower margin cut off.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 " ruledLines="30" writtenLines="30">
									<p>Ink-ruling is visible. </p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side are distinguishable. </p>
									<p>The notes from other sources in smaller characters are usually introduced byt the phrase <q>yesh mefareshim</q> or <q>yesh omrim</q>.</p>
									<p>Initial letters of the chapters are written in large square characters.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Italian semi-cursive script, unpunctuated, of the 15th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">Shabtai ben Yehoshu῾a</name> of <placeName>Tivoli</placeName> and <name type="person" role="patron">Shemu᾿el ben Menaḥem</name>: their names inscribed in the colophon (162r) and the opening note (3r), <name type="place">Fiorentino</name>?, <date calendar="Gregorian">1488</date>. Scribe's name is often marked by the initial letters in the lines of a page.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folio 28r - has censor's erasure.</p>
							<p>Folios 1v-2v - an English translation by John Noble Coleman of one of the anti-Christian passages from the commentary.</p>
							<p>Three partially illegible owners' notes in Hebrew, folio 162v, one of them dated <date calendar="Hebrew">371</date> (<date calendar="Gregorian">1611</date>).</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>  	Post-1600. Gold-tooled brown leather.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin when-custom="[5]248" calendar="Hebrew" when="1488"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Italy</name>, C. (<name type="place">Castiglion Fiorentino?</name>, <name type="place">Castelfiorentino</name>? <name type="place">Fiorentina</name>?)</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<p>Rev. <name type="person" role="owner">John Noble Coleman</name> (b. 1793, d. 1872): scholar of the Bible at Queen's College, Oxford: his bookplate affixed to folio 1v and another to the [inner side of the outer cover]. On folio 2r there is a memorandum stating that <name type="person" role="owner">Granville Sharp</name> (b. 1734, d. 1813), theologian and lawyer, was a previous owner of this manuscript, from whom Coleman bought it for 3 guineas.</p>
						</acquisition>
